frameDefinitions: A Color serves as a landmark in color-space, either a point-like landmark (e.g. burnt sienna) or a broader region (e.g. blue).
A Hunter tries to gain Food by way of outsmarting or tracking a living.
The words in this frame describe situations in which an Agent or a Cause injures a Victim.
A Miner attempts to obtain a desirable Resource, rocks and minerals, located in a Place being mined, by digging or tunneling in the ground.
These are words describing situations in which a Perpetrator takes Goods from a  Victim or a Source.
An Employer employs an Employee whose Position entails that the Employee perform certain Tasks in exchange for Compensation.
frameExamples: I really like that shade of <t>blue</t>.
In the Congo, he hunted big game for the first time.
Rod saw his father <t>beating</t> his mother.
I can't believe he <t>pickpocketed</t> my gold watch !
I <t>employed</t> him as Chief Gardener for ten years.
listRoleDefinitions: This role identifies the <fen>Entity</fen> described by the <fen>Color</fen>.
A position in color-space, generally used to describe the quality of some <fen>Entity</fen>.
The <fen>Hunter</fen> is the agent hoping to obtain <fen>Food</fen>.
<fen>Food</fen> is the sought-out item by the <fen>Hunter</fen>.
This is the entity to which the <fen>Hunter</fen> pays attention. It is referred to as <fen>Ground</fen> because it serves as the background or context for the <fen>Food</fen>.
When the <fen>Time</fen> seeking action occurs.
The greater geographic location where the <fen>Hunter</fen> attempts to obtain <fen>Food</fen>.
<fen>Agent</fen> is the person causing the <fen>Victim</fen>'s injury.

The <fen>Victim</fen> is the being or entity that is injured.  If the <fen>Victim</fen> is included in the phrase indicating <fen>Body_part</fen>, the <fen>Victim</fen> role is tagged on a second role layer (see 3rd example).
The <fen>Body_part</fen> identifies the location on the body where the bodily injury takes place.
The <fen>Cause</fen> marks expressions that indicate some non-intentional, typically non-human, force that inflicts harm on the <fen>Victim</fen>
<fen>Time</fen> identifies the time when the harm-causing event occurs.
<fen>Place</fen> identifies the place where the harm causing event occurs.
The <fen>Miner</fen> searches for mineral <fen>Resource</fen>s.
The <fen>Resource</fen> is usually buried in the ground, and is searched for by the <fen>Miner</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Miner</fen> obtains the <fen>Resource</fen>.
The location in which the <fen>Miner</fen> searches for the <fen>Resource</fen>
<fen>Perpetrator</fen> is the person (or other agent) that takes the goods away.
<fen>Victim</fen> is the person (or other sentient being or group) that owns the goods before they are taken away by the perpetrator.
<fen>Goods</fen> is anything (including labor, time, or legal rights) that can be taken away.
<fen>Source</fen> is the initial location of the goods, before they change location.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the theft occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the theft occurs.
The role <fen>Employee</fen> denotes the person who is obligated to perform some <fen>Task</fen> in order to receive <fen>Compensation</fen>.
The <fen>Employer</fen> is the person (or institution) that gives <fen>Compensation</fen> to an <fen>Employee</fen>.
The role <fen>Field</fen> identifies the field in which the <fen>Employee</fen> is employed.
The role <fen>Position</fen> indicates a particular type of employment.
The <fen>Task</fen> indicates the action/duty that the <fen>Employee</fen> is obligated to do for the <fen>Employer</fen>.
The role <fen>Time</fen> identifies the time at whcih the <fen>Employer</fen> hires the <fen>Employee</fen>.
The role <fen>Place</fen> identifies the location where the <fen>Employer</fen> hires the <fen>Employee</fen>.
